editTrim(25.10)                                                editTrim(25.10)

Name
       editTrim - Removes or trims wires

Syntax
       editTrim

       [-help]

       [-keep_floating_stubs]

       [-status {COVER FIXED NOSHIELD ROUTED SHIELD}]

       [-type {float}]

       [-all  |  -selected | -nets <net>* | -layers <layer_names> | -area {<x1
       y1 x2 y2>}]

       Removes or trims wires. Wires are trimmed or removed as follows:

              * Trims floating stubs of wires back to the  closest  connection
                point.

              * Removes wires that do not have electrical connections to other
                wires or pins (floating wires).

              * Removes wires with only one connection to another wire or pin,
                along  with  connecting vias. Removing a wire with one connec-
                tion might cause the wire to which the  just-removed  wire  is
                connected  to change from being a wire with two connections to
                a wire with one connection and thus it will also  be  removed.
                This  process  is  repeated until no wires with one connection
                are left.

                Note: The editTrim command recognizes patch wires and  detects
                the patch wire connection with the via. Therefore, it does not
                delete  patch  wires  even if they are connected from only one
                side.

              * Trims shield wires along with signal wires.

              * Trims wires to support 45-degree wire segments.

       Notes

              * The editTrim command recognizes Through Silicon Via (TSV) con-
                nections and detects the backside wire connection with the TSV
                so it does not remove the backside routes connected to TSV.

              * The editTrim command does not trim metal fill segments.

Parameters
       -help  Prints the usage of the command. For a detailed  description  of
              the command, use the man command:

              man editTrim

       -all   Trims all special wires and floating stubs.

       -area {<x1 y1 x2 y2>}
              Specifies  the  coordinates  for the box area from which to trim
              the wires. Here:

              * x1 - Specifies the lower left x coordinate.

              * y1 - Specifies the lower left y coordinate.

              * x2 - Specifies the upper right x coordinate.

              * y2 - Specifies the upper right y coordinate.

              Only the wires that overlap with  the  specified  box  area  are
              trimmed. The wires that just touch the box area are not trimmed.

       -keep_floating_stubs
              Selects  the  floating  wires  but  does not remove the floating
              stubs. Use this parameter if you want to assess the  impact  be-
              fore actually trimming.

       -layers <layer_names>
              Specifies the layers from which to trim wires. If you are speci-
              fying multiple layers, enclose the layer names in braces.

              Default: If you do not specify this parameter, the command trims
              wires on all layers.

       -nets <net>*
              Trims  wires  on  the nets you specify. You can use wildcards to
              specify the nets.

       -selected
              Trims selected wires. Use the editSelect command to  select  the
              wires. This is the default value.

       -status {COVER FIXED NOSHIELD ROUTED SHIELD}
              Allows  you  to filter the wires to be trimmed by status. If you
              specify -status without specifying  -all,  -nets, or  -selected,
              the tool will trim selected wires with the specified status.

       -type {float}
              Removes only wires that do not have  electrical  connections  to
              other wires or pins (floating wires). The tool will not trim the
              wire with connection to other wires at one end if this option is
              specified.

Examples
              * The following command trims the wires overlapping the box area
                specified by the coordinates {<x1 y1 x2 y2>}:

                editTrim -area {<x1 y1 x2 y2>}

                Before

                After

              *

                The following command trims the wires in the specified layers:

                editTrim -layers {Metal1 Metal3}

